---
import MainLayout from '../../layouts/MainLayout.astro';
---
<MainLayout title="Sports Banquet Seating Chart Tool" description="Free printable seating chart templates for high school sports banquets and athletic celebrations. Organize tables by team, class year, or mixed seating.">
  <div class="breadcrumbs">
    <div class="container">
      <a href="/">Home</a> <span>/</span> <a href="/checklist/">Checklist</a> <span>/</span> <strong>Seating Chart</strong>
    </div>
  </div>

  <section class="page-header">
    <div class="container">
      <h1>Sports Banquet Seating Chart Templates</h1>
      <p>Smart seating arrangements can make or break your banquet. Use these templates to find the right setup for your event.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="container">
      <div class="page-wrapper">
        <h2>Why Seating Matters</h2>
        <p>Good seating creates good energy. When athletes sit with a mix of teammates across grade levels, conversations flow better, underclassmen feel included, and the whole event feels cohesive. Poor seating leads to cliques, awkward silences, and a disjointed experience.</p>

        <h2>Three Seating Strategies</h2>

        <h3>1. The Mixed Team Approach (Recommended)</h3>
        <p>Mix athletes across grade levels and positions. Place seniors at each table as table captains to lead conversation and welcome younger teammates.</p>
        <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Programs wanting to build team unity beyond the season.</p>

        <h3>2. The Varsity / JV Split</h3>
        <p>Varsity athletes at tables near the front/head table, JV and freshmen in the remaining tables. Easier to organize but can feel hierarchical.</p>
        <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Large programs with 100+ athletes where mixing isn't practical.</p>

        <h3>3. Position / Unit Grouping</h3>
        <p>Offensive line, defensive backs, forwards, midfielders — group athletes by position. Creates natural conversation and shared memories.</p>
        <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Football, soccer, and other sports with clear position groups.</p>

        <h2>Sample Table Layouts</h2>

        <h3>Round Tables (8-10 per table)</h3>
        <p>Best for conversation. One centerpiece per table. Suggested for 40-120 guests.</p>

        <h3>Long Rectangular Tables (12-16 per table)</h3>
        <p>Best for buffet-style service. Place a centerpiece every 4-6 feet. Suggested for larger groups.</p>

        <h3>Head Table Setup</h3>
        <p>Position coaches, athletic director, and senior class at a long table facing the room at the front. Ensure the head table also has centerpieces that match the rest of the room.</p>

